at|^b@2^z@3|
cs|5|cp|6|fp|t|
at|
^-{ Introduction to Chapter 5 }
^-|fp||cp||at|
Bridge players use the term constructive to describe an auction in which only one partnership is bidding and the other partnership passes throughout. Competitive auctions are those in which at least one member of each partnership bids or doubles at least once at some point during the bidding. In practice, approximately half of the auctions of bridge deals that you play will be competitive in nature so it is important to make agreements with your regular partner about what your bids mean in these auctions. 

Most introductory textbooks on bridge (as well as the original Learn to Play Bridge program) focus largely on constructive bidding. That is a good thing because competitive auctions tend to be more complex than constructive auctions. In addition, it is not really possible to master some of the concepts of competitive bidding without a thorough understanding of bidding in the absence of competition.

The SAYC bidding system contains a full range of agreements and includes several popular conventions that will help you and your partner bid more effectively in competitive auctions. The purpose of this chapter is to introduce you to the methods that SAYC uses when both partnerships are involved in the bidding.

In particular you will learn about how the responder adjusts his strategy when his partner opens the bidding and the next hand either makes a takeout double or overcalls. You will also learn about 2 popular conventions (Michaels cuebids and the Unusual notrump) that your partnership can use to enter the auction when one of the opponents opens the bidding.
|
qx|5.1|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|tb||n#|5|At|Before we get into the specifics of how SAYC deals with various competitive bidding situations, let's review some of the basic principles of competitive bidding. The first question to explore is why a partnership should get involved in the auction when one of the opponents has opened the bidding. Here are 3 reasons why doing this can be a good strategy:

|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. Sometimes your partnership will be able to succeed in a contract 
 of your own when one of the opponents opens the bidding. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 2. Sometimes your partnership will fail in a contract you bid, but this will be a good 
 sacrifice because the opponents could have made a contract of their own. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 3. By getting involved in the auction after one of the opponents opens the bidding, you 
 can make it more difficult for them to discover the best possible final contract to play in. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


at|Why is life more difficult for the opponents when your partnership gets involved in the bidding? For one thing, every bid that you and your partner make takes away some bidding space from the opponents. The less bidding space they have, the harder it is for them to exchange the information that they need in order to select the best final contract.

|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|In addition, by turning the opponents' constructive auction into a competitive auction, you may create a bidding situation that the opponents are not familiar with. Most partnerships spend a lot of time working on their constructive bidding and they will not usually get confused as to the meanings of their bids if you and your partner pass throughout. There is a much better chance that the opponents will have a misunderstanding if you and your partner bid, thereby creating an auction that they have not discussed before.

|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
As in constructive bidding, one of the main goals of competitive bidding is to find a good trump fit. The more combined trumps a partnership has, the less it matters whether or not a partnership has a lot of high card points. Here is an example:

|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


cs|3|at|^B { |ih|psqj863ht9752d73ct|at| }    @2|
ht|f|n#|5|at|Suppose that you hold this hand. One of your opponents opens the bidding and your partner made a weak jump overcall in spades. You now know that your partnership has a lot of spades between them, but that the opponents have the vast majority of high cards in the deck.
^b@2
|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|Do not be afraid because of your lack of HCP! You should feel perfectly safe about bidding to at least the 4-level in spades. It is true that you are most unlikely to make 4@S and that if the opponents let you play in 4@S, they will certainly double you in this contract. That should not be a matter of concern for 2 reasons:

|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 4@S does not rate to fail by much. Having a big trump fit makes up for having few HCP! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ The opponents certainly can make a game contract and they can probably make a slam. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


at|Your partner is likely to have 6 spades headed by the @SAK and little else in the way of high cards. The opponents have 2 spades between them at the most. It is possible that your partnership can win a trick on defense in spades, but it is not at all unlikely that one of the opponents has a spade void. Even if 4@S doubled is the final contract and even if this contract fails by a few tricks, your result will almost certainly represent a good sacrifice.

|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|7|cs|1|at|
^-{ Having a big trump fit with your partner increases the offensive 
 potential and decreases the defensive potential of your hand. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|Having a lot of trumps increases a hand's offensive potential because the more combined cards in a given suit that a partnership has, the more tricks they are likely to take if that suit ends up being trump. At the same time, the partnership's potential for winning defensive tricks decreases for 2 reasons:

|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 1. If your partnership has a big fit there is a good chance that 
 the opponents have a big fit in one of the other 3 suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 2. If your partnership has a big fit then your high cards in that suit will not win many 
 tricks on defense (since at least one of the opponents will be short in your suit). }
^-
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


at|To summarize, the main objective for a partnership to get involved in a competitive auction is in order to try to find a trump fit. If they are able to do so, they should not be afraid to raise the suit of their fit even if they do not have a lot of high cards.

Having a good trump fit will protect your partnership from losing a lot of tricks and it will increase the chances of the opponents being able to succeed in a contract of their own. At the same time, getting involved in the opponents' constructive auction will make it harder for them to discover their own best contract. 

In this chapter we will see that SAYC contains some good tools for overcoming the difficulties that are presented when the opponents get involved in your auctions.

|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


qx|oppX,Bidding after an opponent's takeout double|

nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|5|cp|6|tb|y|fp|t|at|
^-{  Bidding after an opponent's takeout double  }
^-|fp||at|
|cp||at|Suppose that you are sitting South and your partner, North, opens the bidding (with 1@D for example) and East makes a takeout double. You have to decide what call to make. Should you make the same call that you would have made if East had passed or does East's takeout double change the strategy that you should employ on certain hands?

|cs|1|at|^-{ |ia| 1dd?|at| }
^-
|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


at|The first thought that might cross your mind is that East's takeout double does not remove any of the options you would have had if he had passed instead. You can still pass if you want and you can still make any call between 1@H and 7NT. While all of this is true, East's takeout double affects the choices that you have in 2 ways:

|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 1. You could redouble - a call that would not have been available if East had passed. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ 2. If you pass here you can be fairly certain that you will get another chance to bid later.
 That would not be the case if East had passed instead of making a takeout double. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


at|The fact that you can now redouble has a lot of implications as far as your other possible actions go. The fact that you can pass and expect to have another chance to bid is not particularly relevant on most hands that you will be dealt when the bidding goes this way.

|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
However, there are some hands where you would respond to North's opening bid if East had passed, but that you should be happy to pass if instead East makes a takeout double. This is really a matter of judgment as opposed to your choice of bidding system.

|ht|f|n#|5|at|^B{ |cs|1|ia| 1dp?|at| } ^O{ |cs|1|ia| 1dd?|at| } 

|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


cs|3|at|^B  {|ih|ps8ha65dq54c876532|at|}    @2
|ht|k|n^|g|at|Consider this hand for example. With 6 HCP |
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


at|and 2 long suit points for the 6-card club suit, this hand is worth 8 total points. 6 total points is enough to keep the bidding alive when your partner opens so it seems that you should do ^*Isomething^*N with this hand after North's 1@D opening bid.
@0^b@2
|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


at|Unfortunately, there is no satisfying bid that you can make. Your partner would expect you to have at least 4 cards in hearts for a 1@H response |
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


at|and you should not raise his minor suit to 2@D without at least 4-card support. |
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


at|You do have a 6-card club suit, but you would need a much better hand (or at least much better clubs) to make a two over one response of 2@C. |
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


at|1NT is the correct bid with this hand, but with a singleton in spades that call is not exactly appetizing.

|ht|f|n#|5|at|^B{ |cs|1|ia| 1dp!1n|at| }

|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


ht|f|n#|5|at|^O{ |cs|1|ia| 1dd!p|at| }
|ht|r|n#|5|at|Once East makes a takeout double of 1@D, things are different. You can now pass and be confident that you will have another chance to bid. You can bid at your next turn if your judgment tells you to do so. The fact that your partner will have another turn to bid before you do will help make your decision easier on the next round of bidding.

|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3

|at|^B{ |cs|1|ia| 1dp!1n|at| } ^O{ |cs|1|ia| 1dd!1n|at| } 

The 1NT response to an opening bid is really a catchall for hands that are too strong to pass, too weak to bid a new suit at the 2-level, and have the wrong distribution for any other action. After a takeout double the 1NT response is different:

|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ After your partner opens the bidding and the next hand makes a 
 takeout double, do not bid 1NT unless you want to bid 1NT! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


cs|3|at|^^^^^B{ |ih|psqt4hkJ8d643ckt76|at|}   @2
|ht|n|at|You might ^*Iwant^*N to bid 1NT if you had a hand that looked like this (that is, a balanced hand with sound values for a response and stoppers in the unbid suits).
^b@2

|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


at|Whether or not you should bid 1NT over a takeout double is a matter of judgment more than anything else. One way to think about this situation is to ask yourself if you would be happy if 1NT became the final contract. If the answer to that question is "yes" then 1NT is probably a good bid to make! If the answer to that question is "no" then you would probably be better off passing.

|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|At|Here is another example of the same principle:

|ht|c|n#|5|at|^B{ |cs|1|ia| 1dp?|at| } ^O{ |cs|1|ia| 1dd?|at| } 

|cs|3|at|^B  {|ih|ps6532hj76dq43ck54|at|}    @2
|
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


ht|g|n#|5|at|This is another hand with 6 HCP, but this hand has no redeeming qualities in terms of its distribution. |
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


at|Still, it would be correct to respond 1@S to North's 1@D if the auction was purely constructive. 
^b@2
|ht|c|n#|5|at|^B{ |cs|1|ia| 1dp!1s|at| }
|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


ht|l|at|Bidding such a weak 4-card suit (especially with such a poor hand) is never an attractive proposition, but you really have no choice other than to bid 1@S on this hand after East passes over 1@D.

|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


ht|c|n#|5|at|^O{ |cs|1|ia| 1dd!p|at| }
|ht|q|n#|7|at|When East doubles 1@D, things are different. You now have the choice of passing and with this particular hand you should exercise that choice!

|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ After your partner opens the bidding and the next hand makes a takeout double, 
 do not bid a new suit at the 1-level unless you do not mind being raised by your partner! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


ht|w|n#|8|at|Here, if you bid 1@S, your partner might well raise you with 3-card support. Given that you have a weak hand, weak spades, and that East rates to have good spades for his takeout double, you really do not want to play this hand in spades. Since you do not want your spades to be raised, you should not give your partner a chance to do this. Pass for now - there will be a "later"!

|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|At|To summarize, if your partner opens the bidding and the next hand passes, you should always respond if you have 6 or more total points. The same is not true if your partner opens and the next hand makes a takeout double.

|ht|e|n#|5|at|^B{ |cs|1|ia| 1dp?|at| } ^O  { |cs|1|ia| 1dd?|at| } 

|
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Passing over an opponent's takeout double does not deny 6 (or more) total points. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


at|Do not get the impression that you should look for opportunities to pass over an opponent's takeout double with hands that you would normally respond to an opening bid. Just be aware of the fact that you can pass over an opponent's takeout double and expect to have another chance to bid. If your judgment tells you to take this course on a particular hand, you should back your judgment even if that hand contains 6 or more total points.

|
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Bidding a new suit at the 1-level over an opponent's takeout double is forcing,
 but the responder does not promise any more than 6 total points for such an action. }
^-

|
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


cs|1|At|^B{ |ia| 1dd1sp?|at| }   @2
|ht|r|n#|6|at|The opener cannot pass 1@S because that call is forcing. 1@S here promises at least 6 total points and at least 4 spades. The responder should make the same rebid that he would have made if East had passed over 1@D. |
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|
cs|3|ht|b|at|^C{|ih|pskt976h54dq62ct73|at|} |ht|c|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd?|at| }



|at|This hand, for example, has 5 HCP |
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


at|and 1 long suit point for the 5-card spade suit. 6 total points is the very minimum you can have for a response to an opening bid, |
pg| ***** 48 ***** |


at|but you should still respond 1@S even after East's takeout double. Even though your hand is not very strong, you do have a reasonable 5-card spade suit and you should not mind if your partner feels inclined to raise you.

|ht|c|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd!1s|at| }
|
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


cs|3|ht|n|at|^C{|ih|ps54haj96dj87cqt85|at|} |ht|o|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd?|at| }



|at|This next hand, with 8 HCP, is a little stronger than the first example. |
pg| ***** 50 ***** |


at|The heart suit contains only 4 cards, but as far as 4-card suits go, this one is pretty strong. |
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


at|You should respond 1@H over East's takeout double, just like you would if East had passed. If your partner has heart support and wants to raise, you should not be afraid to be the declarer in a contract with hearts as the trump suit. 
|ht|o|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd1h|at| }
|
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
The responder's ability to pass over an opponent's takeout double on some hands with which he would have responded in the absence of a takeout double does have some impact on the responder's strategy. However, the fact that the responder has a new call available (the redouble) has much more serious implications in these competitive auctions.

|cs|1|At|^-{ |ia| 1dd!r|at| }
^-
|
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ With most hands containing 10 or more HCP the responder should redouble 
 when an opponent makes a takeout double of his partner's opening bid. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


at|The basic message sent by the redouble of an opponent's takeout double is as follows:

|
pg| ***** 55 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Partner, we have the majority of the high cards between us. Either our side 
 is going to play the contract or we are going to double the opponents. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


at|Notice that only high card points (and not total points) are considered for these redoubles. When a player has 10 or more HCP and he hears his partner open the bidding, he is in a strong position to know that the deal ^*ibelongs to^*N his partnership. 

It is therefore reasonable for the partnership to adopt a strategy of either playing the contract themselves or doubling the opponents. The responder can inform the opener of this good news by redoubling his opponent's takeout double.|
pg| ***** 57 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Here is an example of the redouble in action:

|cs|3|ht|d|at|^C{|ih|psaj97hkt86d42caj9|at|} |ht|e|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd?|at| }



|
pg| ***** 58 ***** |


at|This hand has 13 HCP |
pg| ***** 59 ***** |


at|and strong holdings in each of the 3 unbid suits. |
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


at|While it would be safe to bid a forcing 1@H with this hand, that would be letting the opponents off the hook. |
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


at|^^^^Given North's opening bid, East's takeout double, and the strength of the responder's hand, there is very little in the way of high cards left for West to hold. It appears that East picked a bad moment to enter the bidding. You should make him pay for trying to disrupt your constructive auction!

|
pg| ***** 62 ***** |


ht|e|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd!r|at| }

|ht|q|n#|3|at|You should redouble to let your partner know that you have at least 10 HCP. Furthermore, you should be prepared to double the opponents wherever they choose to play. |
pg| ***** 63 ***** |


at|^^^^If North does not have a defensive hand (perhaps he has a minimum opening bid with a very long diamond suit) he will let you know about it (perhaps by rebidding 2@D before you have a chance to double the opponents). You can then look for a game contract (probably 3NT) of your own.

|ht|e|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1ddr1h!2d|at| }

|
pg| ***** 64 ***** |


ht|x|cs|2|At|^-{ Redouble is a suggestion that doubling the opponents might be a good idea, but 
the opener should express his preference for offense if his hand is distributional. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 65 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Do not think that you have to redouble every time you have 10 or more HCP. For example:

|cs|3|ht|d|at|^C{|ih|phat62skqt98dq765|at|} |ht|e|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd?|at| }



|
pg| ***** 66 ***** |


at|This hand has 11 HCP which is more than enough to redouble over East's takeout double of your partner's 1@D opening bid. |
pg| ***** 67 ***** |


at|However, with this particular hand it would be a mistake to redouble. Instead you should start by bidding 1@S just like you would have done if East had passed. As we have seen, bidding a new suit at the 1-level over an opponent's takeout double if forcing - your partner cannot pass you in 1@S.
|ht|e|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd!1s|at| }
|
pg| ***** 68 ***** |


ht|q|at|This hand is strongly oriented toward offense (as opposed to defense) and there are a lot of things you would like to tell your partner about your hand. Exploring for an 8-card major suit fit in spades |
pg| ***** 69 ***** |


at|or hearts should be your first priority. |
pg| ***** 70 ***** |


At|If such a fit cannot be found, you will want to tell your partner about your excellent support for his diamond suit. 

|
pg| ***** 71 ***** |


at|This hand has several important features to describe and you should start describing these as soon as possible. Redoubling would only complicate the bidding and make it harder for you to tell your partner everything he should know about your hand. Furthermore, the opponents are certain to have a good fit in clubs. Even if your partner makes a penalty double of a club contract, you should not want to defend with a void in their trump suit.

|
pg| ***** 72 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
The last hand we looked at is a rather extreme example of the type of hand with which you should not redouble despite having 10 or more HCP.

|cs|3|ht|d|n#|0|at|^C{|ih|pskqt98hat62dq765|at|} |ht|e|n#|0|at|^N {|cs|1|ia| 1dd!1s|at| }



|
pg| ***** 73 ***** |


at|There are no firm rules about when the responder should redouble and when he should ignore the opponent's takeout double and try to bid his hand as he would have if there had been no takeout double. The decision about whether or not to redouble is really a matter of judgment. Here are some guidelines to keep in mind:

|
pg| ***** 74 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Redouble is a suggestion that your partnership should consider doubling the opponents. 
 If your hand is oriented toward offense (instead of defense), it is usually best not to redouble. }

|
pg| ***** 75 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ Balanced hands, especially those that lack strong support 
 for the opener's suit, are good hands with which to redouble. }

|
pg| ***** 76 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ Having a singleton or void in an unbid suit is a sign that a redouble may not be best. 
 The opponents are very likely to have a good trump fit in the responder's short suit. }

|
pg| ***** 77 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ Remember that failure to redouble does not deny holding 10 or more HCP! }
|
pg| ***** 78 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|n#|5|at|Consider the following actions for the responder after his partner opens the bidding and the next hand makes a takeout double. In each case the responder's bid would usually suggest a hand with at least 10 HCP if there had been no takeout double: 

|
pg| ***** 79 ***** |


at|^B{ |ia| 1dd!2c|at| } |cs|2|n#|8|at|^M{ A two over one response in a new suit }

|
pg| ***** 80 ***** |


cs|1|at|
^B{ |ia| 1dd!2s|at| } |cs|2|n#|8|at|^M{ A jump shift response }

|
pg| ***** 81 ***** |


cs|1|at|
^B{ |ia| 1dd!2n|at| } |cs|2|n#|8|at|{^M A jump to 2NT }

|
pg| ***** 82 ***** |


cs|1|at|
^B{ |ia| 1dd!3d|at| } |cs|2|n#|8|at|^M{ A limit raise }


|
pg| ***** 83 ***** |


cs|4|n#|5|at|When East makes a takeout double, South has a way of telling his partner that he has a strong hand (he can redouble). It therefore makes sense to use the responses that would show a strong hand in the absence of a takeout double for some other purpose once a takeout double is made. In the SAYC bidding system, the meanings of South's actions in the 4 auctions above change as a result of East's takeout double. 

