nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|5|cp|6|tb|y|fp|t|at|
^-{  Bidding after an opponent's takeout double - Review and Exercises  }
^-|fp||at|
|cp||at|This chapter started with a look at the differences between constructive auctions (those in which only 1 partnership is involved in the bidding) and competitive auctions (those in which at least one member of each partnership bids or doubles at least once). 

Even though most introductory books on bridge focus on constructive bidding, having strong agreements about competitive auctions is important. About half of the bridge deals that you will ever play will include competitive bids and there are a huge number of possible ways that the bidding can go once both partnerships get involved. Fortunately, the SAYC bidding system has some excellent methods in place for making your decisions in competitive auctions easier and more effective.

Here is a reminder of 3 good reasons why a partnership should get involved in the auction after the opposing partnership has opened the bidding:

|
pg| ***** 153 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. Sometimes your partnership will be able to succeed in a contract 
 of your own when one of the opponents opens the bidding. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 154 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 2. Sometimes your partnership will fail in a contract you bid, but this will be a good 
 sacrifice because the opponents could have made a contract of their own. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 155 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 3. By getting involved in the auction after one of the opponents opens the bidding, you 
 can make it more difficult for them to discover the best possible final contract to play in. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 156 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|tb||n#|5|at|Being able to compete effectively for the final contract against the opposing partnership is largely about trying to find a trump fit. 

|
pg| ***** 157 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Having a big trump fit with your partner increases the offensive 
 potential and decreases the defensive potential of your hand. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 158 ***** |


at|You already know that having a lot of combined cards in a given suit tends to result in your partnership winning a lot of tricks when that suit is trump. It is less obvious why a big fit for your side tends to limit the defensive potential of your partnership's hands. Here are 2 reasons why this is the case:

|
pg| ***** 159 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 1. If your partnership has a big fit there is a good chance that 
 the opponents have a big fit in one of the other 3 suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 160 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 2. If your partnership has a big fit then your high cards in that suit will not win many 
 tricks on defense (since at least one of the opponents will be short in your suit). }
^-
|
pg| ***** 161 ***** |


at|The bulk of this chapter to this point has dealt with auctions in which your partner opens the bidding with 1 of a suit and the next hand makes a takeout double. As we have seen, the responder has a lot of options available when the bidding starts like this.

|cs|1|at|^-{|ia| 1dd?|at|}
